            "source": [
                "# PCA Series | Chapter 2: High-Dimensional PCA — When N << d\n",
                "\n",
                "> **Chapter Goal:** Understand what goes wrong when your dataset has fewer samples than features ($N < d$) — why the covariance matrix becomes singular, why standard PCA fails, and how **Dual PCA** recovers the principal components efficiently. Master **Random Matrix Theory** and the **Marchenko-Pastur Law** to distinguish real signal from noise eigenvalues — a powerful technique in genomics, finance, and neuroscience.\n",
                "\n",
                "---"
            ]
        },
        {
            "cell_type": "markdown",
            "id": "problem",
            "metadata": {},
            "source": [
                "## 1. The High-Dimensional Problem: When N < d\n",
                "\n",
                "### **When Does This Arise?**\n",
                "| Domain | $N$ | $d$ | Ratio |\n",
                "| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n",
                "| Gene expression (microarray) | 100–1000 patients | 10,000–50,000 genes | $N/d \\approx 0.02$ |\n",
                "| fMRI neuroscience | 20–100 subjects | 50,000+ voxels | $N/d \\approx 0.001$ |\n",
                "| Text (TF-IDF) | 1,000 docs | 100,000 vocabulary | $N/d = 0.01$ |\n",
                "| Small-$N$ clinical trials | 30 patients | 200 biomarkers | $N/d = 0.15$ |\n",
                "\n",
                "### **What Happens to the Covariance Matrix?**\n",
                "$$\\Sigma = \\frac{1}{N-1} X^T X \\in \\mathbb{R}^{d \\times d}$$\n",
                "\n",
                "$X \\in \\mathbb{R}^{N \\times d}$ has rank at most $N$ (at most $N$ linearly independent rows). Therefore $X^T X$ (and $\\Sigma$) has rank at most $N$.\n",
                "\n",
                "**Consequences when $N < d$:**\n",
                "1. **$\\Sigma$ is singular:** $\\det(\\Sigma) = 0$ — cannot be inverted.\n",
                "2. **At most $N-1$ non-zero eigenvalues** (not $d$): PCA can extract at most $N-1$ meaningful PCs.\n",
                "3. **$d-N+1$ eigenvalues are exactly zero:** Directions in null space of $X$.\n",
                "4. **Standard covariance eigendecomposition is infeasible:** $\\Sigma \\in \\mathbb{R}^{d \\times d}$ — for $d=50{,}000$, this is a $2.5 \\times 10^9$ entry matrix. Just storing it requires ~20 GB RAM.\n",
                "\n",
                "---"
            ]
        },
        {
            "cell_type": "markdown",
            "id": "dual_pca",
            "metadata": {},
            "source": [
                "## 2. Dual PCA: The Key Idea\n",
                "\n",
                "### **The Central Insight**\n",
                "Instead of eigendecomposing $\\Sigma = X^T X / (N-1) \\in \\mathbb{R}^{d \\times d}$, eigendecompose the much smaller **Gram matrix**:\n",
                "$$G = X X^T \\in \\mathbb{R}^{N \\times N}$$\n",
                "\n",
                "When $N \\ll d$, the Gram matrix is tiny (e.g., $100 \\times 100$ instead of $50{,}000 \\times 50{,}000$).\n",
                "\n",
                "**Key theorem:** $X^T X$ and $X X^T$ share the same **non-zero eigenvalues**.\n",
                "\n",
                "Proof: If $X X^T \\vec{u} = \\lambda \\vec{u}$ with $\\lambda \\neq 0$, let $\\vec{v} = X^T \\vec{u}$. Then:\n",
                "$$X^T X \\vec{v} = X^T X (X^T \\vec{u}) = X^T (X X^T) \\vec{u} = X^T (\\lambda \\vec{u}) = \\lambda (X^T \\vec{u}) = \\lambda \\vec{v}$$\n",
                "So $\\vec{v}$ is an eigenvector of $X^T X$ with the same eigenvalue $\\lambda$. QED.\n",
                "\n",
                "---"
            ]
        },
        {
            "cell_type": "markdown",
            "id": "dual_pca_algorithm",
            "metadata": {},
            "source": [
                "## 3. Dual PCA Algorithm: Full Derivation\n",
                "\n",
                "**Input:** Centered data $X \\in \\mathbb{R}^{N \\times d}$ with $N < d$.\n",
                "\n",
                "**Step 1: Compute the Gram matrix** ($N \\times N$, cheap!):\n",
                "$$G = X X^T$$\n",
                "\n",
                "**Step 2: Eigendecompose $G$** (an $N \\times N$ matrix — fast):\n",
                "$$G = U_G \\Lambda_G U_G^T$$\n",
                "where $U_G \\in \\mathbb{R}^{N \\times N}$ has orthonormal columns and $\\Lambda_G = \\text{diag}(\\lambda_1, ..., \\lambda_{N})$ with $\\lambda_1 \\geq ... \\geq \\lambda_N \\geq 0$.\n",
                "\n",
                "**Step 3: Recover PCs in the original $d$-dimensional space**:\n",
                "Using the proof above: $\\vec{v}_k = X^T \\vec{u}_{G,k}$, but normalize:\n",
                "$$V = X^T U_G \\Lambda_G^{-1/2}$$\n",
                "\n",
                "where $\\Lambda_G^{-1/2} = \\text{diag}(\\lambda_1^{-1/2}, ..., \\lambda_{N-1}^{-1/2})$ (discard zero eigenvalues).\n",
                "\n",
                "**Verify:** $V^T V = \\Lambda_G^{-1/2} U_G^T X X^T U_G \\Lambda_G^{-1/2} = \\Lambda_G^{-1/2} \\Lambda_G \\Lambda_G^{-1/2} = I$ ✅ (columns of $V$ are orthonormal)\n",
                "\n",
                "**Step 4: PC scores** (the projections):\n",
                "$$Z = XV = X X^T U_G \\Lambda_G^{-1/2} = G U_G \\Lambda_G^{-1/2} = U_G \\Lambda_G \\Lambda_G^{-1/2} = U_G \\Lambda_G^{1/2}$$\n",
                "\n",
                "So $Z = U_G \\Lambda_G^{1/2}$ — obtained directly without projecting through $d$-dimensional space!\n",
                "\n",
                "### **Computational Comparison**\n",
                "| Method | Matrix to decompose | Size | Cost |\n",
                "| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n",
                "| Standard PCA | $\\Sigma = X^T X/(N-1)$ | $d \\times d$ | $O(d^3)$ — infeasible for large $d$ |\n",
                "| Dual PCA | $G = X X^T$ | $N \\times N$ | $O(N^2 d + N^3)$ — feasible when $N \\ll d$ |\n",
                "\n",
                "### **The Unified Solution: SVD of $X$**\n",
                "Instead of choosing between standard and dual PCA, use SVD of $X$ directly:\n",
                "$$X = U \\Sigma_s V^T$$\n",
                "- $V$ = right singular vectors = PC directions (in $\\mathbb{R}^d$) ← standard PCA would give these\n",
                "- $U$ = left singular vectors = PC score directions (in $\\mathbb{R}^N$) ← dual PCA gives these\n",
                "- $Z = U\\Sigma_s$ = PC scores\n",
                "\n",
                "**SVD automatically picks the smaller computation**, whether $N > d$ or $N < d$.\n",
                "\n",
                "---"
            ]
        },
        {
            "cell_type": "markdown",
            "id": "sample_bias",
            "metadata": {},
            "source": [
                "## 4. Sample Eigenvalue Bias: PCA is Unreliable in High Dimensions\n",
                "\n",
                "Even when you can compute PCA (e.g., using Dual PCA), the results may be **statistically unreliable** when $N$ is small relative to $d$.\n",
                "\n",
                "### **What Goes Wrong**\n",
                "The sample covariance matrix $\\hat{\\Sigma}$ is a noisy estimate of the true population covariance $\\Sigma^*$. When $N \\gg d$, this noise is small. But when $N$ is comparable to $d$:\n",
                "\n",
                "- **Sample eigenvalues are biased upward** — the top eigenvalue $\\hat{\\lambda}_1$ systematically overestimates $\\lambda_1^*$.\n",
                "- **Sample eigenvectors are inconsistent** — they may be nearly orthogonal to the true eigenvectors.\n",
                "- **Number of apparent non-zero PCs grows with $d$** — even for a true identity covariance matrix, the sample covariance has a spread of eigenvalues.\n",
                "\n",
                "### **Intuition**\n",
                "With only $N=10$ samples in $d=100$ dimensions, the data matrix has rank 10. Even if the true covariance is $I$ (all features independent, equal variance), the sample covariance $\\hat{\\Sigma}$ will show a range of eigenvalues from near 0 to $\\sim$several — purely due to sampling noise. PCA would spuriously report these as \"signal\".\n",
                "\n",
                "---"
            ]
        },
        {
            "cell_type": "markdown",
            "id": "rmt",
            "metadata": {},
            "source": [
                "## 5. Random Matrix Theory: What Does Pure Noise Look Like?\n",
                "\n",
                "### **The Question**\n",
                "Given a data matrix $X \\in \\mathbb{R}^{N \\times d}$ with i.i.d entries from $\\mathcal{N}(0, \\sigma^2)$ (pure noise — no structure), what is the distribution of eigenvalues of $\\hat{\\Sigma} = X^T X / N$?\n",
                "\n",
                "We need this **noise baseline** to determine which sample eigenvalues are signal and which are just sampling artifacts.\n",
                "\n",
                "### **The Marchenko-Pastur Law**\n",
                "For a random matrix $X$ with $N$ rows and $d$ columns, i.i.d. entries with mean 0 and variance $\\sigma^2$, as $N, d \\to \\infty$ with ratio $\\gamma = d/N$ fixed, the eigenvalue distribution of $\\hat{\\Sigma} = X^T X / N$ converges to the **Marchenko-Pastur distribution** with density:\n",
                "\n",
                "$$p(\\lambda) = \\frac{\\sqrt{(\\lambda_+ - \\lambda)(\\lambda - \\lambda_-)}}{2\\pi \\sigma^2 \\gamma \\lambda} \\quad \\text{for } \\lambda \\in [\\lambda_-, \\lambda_+]$$\n",
                "\n",
                "where the **noise eigenvalue bounds** are:\n",
                "$$\\boxed{\\lambda_\\pm = \\sigma^2 \\left(1 \\pm \\sqrt{\\gamma}\\right)^2 = \\sigma^2 \\left(1 \\pm \\sqrt{\\frac{d}{N}}\\right)^2}$$\n",
                "\n",
                "- $\\lambda_-$: lower bound of noise eigenvalue support\n",
                "- $\\lambda_+$: **upper bound (the noise threshold)** — the largest eigenvalue a noise-only matrix can have\n",
                "- All eigenvalues within $[\\lambda_-, \\lambda_+]$ are **pure noise**.\n",
                "- Any eigenvalue **above $\\lambda_+$** is **signal** — real structure in the data.\n",
                "\n",
                "### **Practical Rule**\n",
                "Choose $k$ = number of eigenvalues of $\\hat{\\Sigma}$ that exceed $\\lambda_+ = \\sigma^2(1 + \\sqrt{d/N})^2$.\n",
                "\n",
                "If $\\sigma^2$ is unknown, estimate it from eigenvalues in the bulk (use the median, which is robust to signal components).\n",
                "\n",
                "---"
            ]
        },
        {
            "cell_type": "markdown",
            "id": "choosing_k_highdim",
            "metadata": {},
            "source": [
                "## 6. Practical Rules for Choosing $k$ in High Dimensions\n",
                "\n",
                "| Method | Rule | Best When |\n",
                "| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n",
                "| **Marchenko-Pastur threshold** | Keep $\\lambda_k > \\sigma^2(1+\\sqrt{d/N})^2$ | $N, d$ both large, Gaussian-like noise |\n",
                "| **Kaiser rule** | Keep $\\lambda_k > 1$ (for correlation matrix) | Correlation PCA, moderate $N/d$ |\n",
                "| **Visual elbow** | Scree plot bend | Quick exploratory analysis |\n",
                "| **Cross-validation** | Min reconstruction error on held-out data | All settings; computationally expensive |\n",
                "| **Permutation test** | Compare $\\lambda_k$ to permuted data eigenvalues | Conservative, robust |\n",
                "\n",
                "---"
            ]
        },
        {
            "cell_type": "markdown",
            "id": "interview",
            "metadata": {},
            "source": [
                "## 7. Interview Q&A\n",
                "\n",
                "**Q1: What happens to the covariance matrix when $N < d$?**\n",
                "> It becomes rank-deficient: $\\text{rank}(\\Sigma) \\leq N-1 < d$. It has at most $N-1$ non-zero eigenvalues and the remaining $d-N+1$ eigenvalues are exactly zero. It cannot be inverted. Standard eigendecomposition is both computationally infeasible (matrix is $d \\times d$) and statistically meaningless for the zero-eigenvalue directions.\n",
                "\n",
                "**Q2: Explain Dual PCA. Why does it work?**\n",
                "> Dual PCA eigendecomposes the Gram matrix $G = XX^T \\in \\mathbb{R}^{N \\times N}$ instead of $\\Sigma \\in \\mathbb{R}^{d \\times d}$. It works because $XX^T$ and $X^TX$ share the same non-zero eigenvalues. If $XX^T \\vec{u} = \\lambda \\vec{u}$, then $X^T \\vec{u}$ is an eigenvector of $X^TX$ with the same $\\lambda$. So we get the PCs in the original $d$-dimensional space by computing $V = X^T U_G \\Lambda_G^{-1/2}$.\n",
                "\n",
                "**Q3: Why is sample eigenvalue bias a problem?**\n",
                "> When $N$ is small relative to $d$, the sample covariance $\\hat{\\Sigma}$ is a poor estimate of the true $\\Sigma^*$. The top sample eigenvalues are systematically inflated — they overestimate the true eigenvalues. The sample eigenvectors can be nearly orthogonal to the true eigenvectors. PCA results from such data are unstable and can be mostly noise.\n",
                "\n",
                "**Q4: What is the Marchenko-Pastur law and why is it useful?**\n",
                "> The Marchenko-Pastur law describes the eigenvalue distribution of a sample covariance matrix built from pure noise (i.i.d. Gaussian entries). The law gives a noise threshold $\\lambda_+ = \\sigma^2(1 + \\sqrt{d/N})^2$. Any sample eigenvalue above $\\lambda_+$ is statistically unlikely to arise from noise → it indicates real signal. This gives an objective, principled method to choose the number of PCA components.\n",
                "\n",
                "**Q5: Can you always use SVD instead of eigendecomposition for PCA?**\n",
                "> Yes. SVD of $X = U\\Sigma V^T$ always gives the PCA result regardless of whether $N > d$, $N < d$, or $N = d$. The right singular vectors $V$ are the PCs, the PC scores are $Z = U\\Sigma$, and the explained variance per PC is $\\sigma_k^2 / (N-1)$. SVD is always the safer and more general choice.\n",
                "\n",
                "**Q6: How many PCs can you extract when $N < d$?**\n",
                "> At most $N-1$ PCs with non-zero variance (after centering, rank is at most $N-1$). Even if you have $d=50{,}000$ features, with $N=50$ samples, you can extract at most 49 meaningful PCs. The remaining $49{,}951$ directions have zero sample variance.\n",
                "\n",
                "---"
            ]
        },
        {
            "cell_type": "code",
            "execution_count": null,
            "id": "impl_dual_pca",
            "metadata": {},
            "outputs": [],
            "source": [
                "# ─── CELL 1: Dual PCA From Scratch — Verify Equivalence with SVD ───────────────\n",
                "import numpy as np\n",
                "\n",
                "np.random.seed(42)\n",
                "N, d = 30, 500   # N << d: high-dimensional regime\n",
                "k = 5            # number of PCs to extract\n",
                "\n",
                "# Generate high-dim data with k true PCs\n",
                "W_true = np.random.randn(d, k) / np.sqrt(d)  # true loading directions\n",
                "Z_true = np.random.randn(N, k) * np.array([5, 4, 3, 2, 1])  # true scores with decaying variance\n",
                "X = Z_true @ W_true.T + 0.5 * np.random.randn(N, d)  # signal + noise\n",
                "X = X - X.mean(axis=0)  # center\n",
                "\n",
                "print(f\"Data: N={N}, d={d} (N << d)\")\n",
                "print(f\"Covariance matrix Σ would be {d}×{d} = {d*d:,} entries — infeasible!\")\n",
                "print(f\"Gram matrix G is {N}×{N} = {N*N:,} entries — feasible.\")\n",
                "\n",
                "# ── Method 1: Dual PCA (via Gram matrix) ─────────────────────────────────────\n",
                "G = X @ X.T  # N x N  (30 x 30)\n",
                "eigenvalues_G, U_G = np.linalg.eigh(G)\n",
                "# Sort descending, discard near-zero eigenvalues\n",
                "idx = np.argsort(eigenvalues_G)[::-1]\n",
                "eigenvalues_G = eigenvalues_G[idx][:k]; U_G = U_G[:, idx][:, :k]\n",
                "\n",
                "# Recover PC directions in d-dimensional space\n",
                "V_dual = X.T @ U_G @ np.diag(1.0 / np.sqrt(eigenvalues_G))  # d x k\n",
                "Z_dual = U_G @ np.diag(np.sqrt(eigenvalues_G))               # N x k (scores)\n",
                "\n",
                "# ── Method 2: SVD of X directly ──────────────────────────────────────────────\n",
                "U_svd, s_svd, Vt_svd = np.linalg.svd(X, full_matrices=False)\n",
                "V_svd = Vt_svd[:k, :].T   # d x k: right singular vectors\n",
                "Z_svd = U_svd[:, :k] * s_svd[:k]  # N x k: scores\n",
                "\n",
                "# ── Compare (allow sign flips between methods) ────────────────────────────────\n",
                "print(\"\\n===  Eigenvalues from Gram matrix vs SVD² ===\")\n",
                "print(f\"Gram eigenvalues: {eigenvalues_G.round(2)}\")\n",
                "print(f\"SVD σ²:           {(s_svd[:k]**2).round(2)}\")\n",
                "print(f\"Match: {np.allclose(eigenvalues_G, s_svd[:k]**2, rtol=1e-4)}\")\n",
                "\n",
                "# Compare PC directions (up to sign flip)\n",
                "print(\"\\n=== PC Directions Match? (inner products should be ≈ ±1) ===\")\n",
                "for i in range(k):\n",
                "    cos_sim = abs(V_dual[:, i] @ V_svd[:, i])\n",
                "    print(f\"  PC{i+1}: |cos(dual, SVD)| = {cos_sim:.6f}\")\n",
                "\n",
                "# Reconstruction equivalence\n",
                "X_recon_dual = Z_dual @ V_dual.T + X.mean(axis=0)\n",
                "X_recon_svd  = Z_svd @ V_svd.T\n",
                "print(f\"\\nReconstruction error dual: {np.linalg.norm(X - X_recon_dual, 'fro'):.4f}\")\n",
                "print(f\"Reconstruction error SVD:  {np.linalg.norm(X - X_recon_svd, 'fro'):.4f}\")"
            ]
        },
